I have a Python PDF-to-Excel parser (using pdfplumber) that extracts Italian ledger transactions into these columns:

DATA | N.RIF. | N.Prot. | DESCRIZIONE | CONTO | DARE | AVERE

The current implementation relies heavily on x-coordinate column boundaries from the PDF header, but this causes incorrect extraction because some transactions are not perfectly aligned.

The issues are:

1. DATA
- For every transaction, search the entire transaction for a value matching:
  r"^\d{2}/\d{2}/\d{4}$"
- If a valid date exists, populate DATA with that value.
- If no valid date exists, leave DATA blank.
- Do NOT extract dates that belong to DESCRIZIONE.

2. N.RIF.
- The current regex:
  r"^[A-Za-z]$"
  is incorrect.
- N.RIF. should instead be a numeric value.
- It should be identified as the numeric token immediately after DATA and before N.Prot. within the transaction.
- Update the extraction logic accordingly.

3. N.Prot.
- Currently the parser initializes every row with the previous N.Prot., causing blank rows to inherit values incorrectly.
- Only carry forward N.Prot. if the business rule explicitly requires it.
- Otherwise, if the current transaction has no N.Prot., leave it blank.
- Do not pre-populate every row with last_nprot.

4. DESCRIZIONE
- After extracting DATA, N.RIF., N.Prot., CONTO, DARE and AVERE, every remaining token should belong to DESCRIZIONE.
- Dates or numeric values that are actually part of the description should remain in DESCRIZIONE unless they satisfy the extraction rules above.

5. Parsing Strategy
Instead of relying almost entirely on PDF x-coordinate bins, implement a transaction-aware parser:
- Identify DARE/AVERE.
- Identify CONTO.
- Search the remaining tokens for DATA.
- From the remaining tokens, identify N.RIF. and N.Prot. in sequence.
- Everything left becomes DESCRIZIONE.

The goal is to make the extraction robust even when the PDF text is slightly misaligned and not perfectly positioned under the header columns.
